<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Tidyverse on Dusty Turner</title><link>https://www.dustysturner.com/tags/tidyverse/</link><description>Recent content in Tidyverse on Dusty Turner</description><generator>Hugo -- gohugo.io</generator><language>en</language><copyright>© 2026 Dusty Turner</copyright><lastBuildDate>Fri, 17 Jun 2022 00:00:00 +0000</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://www.dustysturner.com/tags/tidyverse/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Fitbit and R Part 1: Accessing Data with the Fitbit API</title><link>https://www.dustysturner.com/post/2022-06-17-fitbit-api-1/</link><pubDate>Fri, 17 Jun 2022 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://www.dustysturner.com/post/2022-06-17-fitbit-api-1/</guid><description>&lt;script src="https://www.dustysturner.com/post/2022-06-17-fitbit-api-1/index_files/header-attrs/header-attrs.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;


&lt;div id="introduction" class="section level2"&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;Introduction&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In part 1 of this series, I will demonstrate how to interact with the &lt;a href="https://www.fitbit.com/"&gt;Fitbit&lt;/a&gt; API in R.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Huge credit to &lt;a href="https://github.com/mrkaye97"&gt;Matt Kaye&lt;/a&gt; for creating the &lt;a href="https://github.com/mrkaye97/fitbitr"&gt;fitbitr package&lt;/a&gt; that provides an interface between R and the &lt;a href="https://dev.fitbit.com/build/reference/web-api/"&gt;Fitbit API&lt;/a&gt;. If you are familiar with R and you have a Fitbit, you should have success following what I have laid out below.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div id="install-the-fitbitr-package" class="section level3"&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Install the &lt;code&gt;fitbitr&lt;/code&gt; package&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;From CRAN:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;pre class="r"&gt;&lt;code&gt;install.packages(&amp;quot;fitbitr&amp;quot;)&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Or the development version from github:&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>The Peloton API Part 2: A Peloton Data Tribute to my Wife</title><link>https://www.dustysturner.com/post/the-peloton-api-part-2/</link><pubDate>Sun, 14 Feb 2021 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://www.dustysturner.com/post/the-peloton-api-part-2/</guid><description>&lt;div id="peloton-r" class="section level1"&gt;
&lt;h1&gt;Peloton R&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In &lt;a href="https://www.dustysturner.com/post/the-peloton-api-part-1/"&gt;part 1&lt;/a&gt; of my Peloton API post, I explored the &lt;a href="https://github.com/bweiher/pelotonR"&gt;&lt;code&gt;pelotonR&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/a&gt; created by &lt;a href="https://github.com/bweiher/"&gt;Ben Weiher’s&lt;/a&gt;. It’s a great package for accessing your Peloton data and I recommend it.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In part 2, I’ll explore a different &lt;code&gt;pelotonR&lt;/code&gt; package from &lt;a href="https://twitter.com/littlemissdata"&gt;Laura Ellis&lt;/a&gt;. She provides a great &lt;a href="https://lgellis.github.io/pelotonR/"&gt;tutorial&lt;/a&gt; to display the functionality. I recommend this one too!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div id="objectives" class="section level2"&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;Objectives&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The objectives for this post are to…&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol style="list-style-type: decimal"&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Show how awesome my wife is.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Highlight the functionality of Laura’s pelotonR package.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Create visualizations from my wife and my Peloton data to show how awesome she is.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Speaking of visualizations, here’s another picture of my wife crushing a Peloton ride&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Wheel Spin Strategy On The Price Is Right</title><link>https://www.dustysturner.com/post/wheel-spin-strategy-on-the-price-is-right/</link><pubDate>Sat, 01 Aug 2020 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://www.dustysturner.com/post/wheel-spin-strategy-on-the-price-is-right/</guid><description>&lt;div id="motivation" class="section level2"&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;Motivation&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Like many, COVID-19 completely altered our lives as the virus spread across the country and became a mainstay in our society. Though my family and I have been spared of tragedy, we’ve had to find ways to replace kid’s activities, work routines, and social interactions with other (hopefully) enriching activities… Like family games.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;center&gt;
&lt;img src="images/cal_beats_reese.jpg" alt="cal" width="500"&gt;
&lt;figcaption&gt;
Ticket to Ride caused a lot of strife between my kids :)
&lt;/figcaption&gt;
&lt;/center&gt;
&lt;p&gt;One thing that we’ve added to our new normal is watching &lt;a href="https://twitter.com/PriceIsRight?s=20"&gt;“The Price is Right”&lt;/a&gt; after dinner. We find it to be a great chance to open up talk of numbers and strategy with our kids.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>ESPN Fantasy Football V3 API for Private Leagues: An R Solution (Finally!)</title><link>https://www.dustysturner.com/post/espn-fantasy-football-v3-api-for-private-leagues-an-r-solution-finally/</link><pubDate>Thu, 12 Sep 2019 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://www.dustysturner.com/post/espn-fantasy-football-v3-api-for-private-leagues-an-r-solution-finally/</guid><description>&lt;script src="https://www.dustysturner.com/post/espn-fantasy-football-v3-api-for-private-leagues-an-r-solution-finally/index_files/htmlwidgets/htmlwidgets.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;link href="https://www.dustysturner.com/post/espn-fantasy-football-v3-api-for-private-leagues-an-r-solution-finally/index_files/jsoneditor/jsoneditor.min.css" rel="stylesheet" /&gt;
&lt;script src="https://www.dustysturner.com/post/espn-fantasy-football-v3-api-for-private-leagues-an-r-solution-finally/index_files/jsoneditor/jsoneditor.min.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;script src="https://www.dustysturner.com/post/espn-fantasy-football-v3-api-for-private-leagues-an-r-solution-finally/index_files/jsonedit-binding/jsonedit.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;


&lt;div id="accessing-espns-new-v3-api-for-private-leagues-how-we-got-here" class="section level3"&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Accessing ESPN’s New V3 API for Private Leagues: How We Got Here&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This marks post 3 of n of my 2019 ESPN Fantasy Football blog posts. In the last few months, ESPN upgraded their API from V2 to V3, breaking all of our previous work &lt;a href="https://dusty-turner.netlify.com/post/espn-yahoo-api-navigation/"&gt;accessing&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="https://dusty-turner.netlify.com/post/mathlete-fantasy-football-analysis2018/"&gt;analysing&lt;/a&gt; the data from the API.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In my last two posts, I explored how to access data from ESPN’s V3 API for &lt;a href="https://dusty-turner.netlify.com/post/espn-fantasy-football-v3-api-an-r-solution/"&gt;public&lt;/a&gt; leagues. My best efforts to access data for private leagues in R fell short. Using the work from my friend &lt;a href="https://twitter.com/thestevemo"&gt;Steve&lt;/a&gt; on his &lt;a href="https://stmorse.github.io/journal/espn-fantasy-v3.html"&gt;blog&lt;/a&gt;, I was able to execute Python code inside R chunks with the library &lt;code&gt;reticulate&lt;/code&gt;. I wrote about that process in &lt;a href="https://dusty-turner.netlify.com/post/espn-fantasy-football-v3-api-an-r-solution/"&gt;post 2&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>ESPN Fantasy Football V3 API for Private Leagues: Python Through R</title><link>https://www.dustysturner.com/post/espn-fantasy-football-v3-api-for-private-leagues-python-through-r/</link><pubDate>Mon, 02 Sep 2019 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://www.dustysturner.com/post/espn-fantasy-football-v3-api-for-private-leagues-python-through-r/</guid><description>&lt;script src="https://www.dustysturner.com/post/espn-fantasy-football-v3-api-for-private-leagues-python-through-r/index_files/kePrint/kePrint.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;link href="https://www.dustysturner.com/post/espn-fantasy-football-v3-api-for-private-leagues-python-through-r/index_files/lightable/lightable.css" rel="stylesheet" /&gt;
